{"type":"text","timestamp":1773440229581,"sessionID":"ses_316bba7bfffeeA1IqckNkl9JmJ","part":{"id":"prt_ce9462c5d0014S0iae9wwJmagp","sessionID":"ses_316bba7bfffeeA1IqckNkl9JmJ","messageID":"msg_ce94624f8001HPCVBb3HTeJ9KI","type":"text","text":"Now I see the key integration point. In `launchSingleHeadless`:\n- Line 254-264: It checks `agentResolutions?.get(feature.id)` for specialized agent content, and falls back to `agent.agent_name` (from persisted state).\n- Line 268-275: It passes `agentName` to `launchHeadless()`.\n\nThe issue: In `resume.ts`, `launchSingleHeadless` is called without `agentResolutions` parameter. This means:\n1. The `agentName` (line 255) still gets set from `agent.agent_name` which was persisted in state — **good** for launching with the correct agent name.\n2. The specialized agent content won't be written to the worktree again (line 256 check will be false) — but the worktree may already have it from the initial launch, or the worktree was cleaned. This is a **potential gap** for retry/resume cases where the worktree is recreated.\n\nHowever, this is a reasonable design: if the worktree is brand new, the agent won't have the specialized content file, but `launchHeadless` will still use the `agentName` which points to `agent.agent_name` from persisted state. The agent binary (opencode) would look for the agent definition in `.opencode/agents/<name>.md` — if it doesn't exist, it would fall back to default behavior.\n\nLet me check if there's any issue, then run the build:","time":{"start":1773440229580,"end":1773440229580}}}
